Input variables:

bank client data:¶

1 - age (numeric) \ 2 - job : type of job (categorical: "admin.","unknown","unemployed","management","housemaid","entrepreneur","student", "blue-collar","self-employed","retired","technician","services") \ 3 - marital : marital status (categorical: "married","divorced","single"; note: "divorced" means divorced or widowed)\ 4 - education (categorical: "unknown","secondary","primary","tertiary")\ 5 - default: has credit in default? (binary: "yes","no")\ 6 - balance: average yearly balance, in euros (numeric) \ 7 - housing: has housing loan? (binary: "yes","no")\ 8 - loan: has personal loan? (binary: "yes","no")

related with the last contact of the current campaign:¶

9 - contact: contact communication type (categorical: "unknown","telephone","cellular") \ 10 - day: last contact day of the month (numeric)\ 11 - month: last contact month of year (categorical: "jan", "feb", "mar", ..., "nov", "dec")\ 12 - duration: last contact duration, in seconds (numeric)\

other attributes:¶

13 - campaign: number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client (numeric, includes last contact)\ 14 - pdays: number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (numeric, -1 means client was not previously contacted)\ 15 - previous: number of contacts performed before this campaign and for this client (numeric)\ 16 - poutcome: outcome of the previous marketing campaign (categorical: "unknown","other","failure","success")\

Output variable (desired target):¶

17 - y - has the client subscribed a term deposit? (binary: "yes","no")

Continuous Variables¶

'age', 'balance', 'day', 'duration', 'campaign', 'pdays', 'previous'

Categorical Variables:¶

'job', 'marital', 'education', 'default', 'housing', 'loan','contact','month', 'poutcome', 'y'

Handling Imbalanced Data: Upsampling¶

In [15]:
# Upsampling
# Since 88% of records didn't respond to the campaign, we're going to use upsampling method to balance data

from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE

sm = SMOTE(random_state=12)
X_balanced, y_balanced = sm.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)
print('X_train shape: ', X_balanced.shape, '', 'y_train shape: ', y_balanced.shape)
print(y_balanced.value_counts())

3. Model Building¶

Logistic Regression¶

In [17]:
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

lr = LogisticRegression(random_state = 42, max_iter=400)
lr.fit(X_balanced,y_balanced)
y_pred = lr.predict(X_test)
print("Logistic Regression","\n")
print("Classification Report","\n")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))


# Confusion Matrix
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

print("Confusion Matrix","\n")
score = round(accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred),3) 
cm1 = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
sns.heatmap(cm1, annot=True, fmt=".1f", linewidths=.3, 
        square = True, cmap = 'PuBu')
plt.ylabel('Actual label')
plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
plt.title('Accuracy Score: {0}'.format(score), size = 12)
plt.show()
print("\n")

# Cross Validation
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

accuracies_lr = cross_val_score(estimator = lr, X = X_balanced, y = y_balanced, cv = 10)
print("Train Accuracy (mean): %",accuracies_lr.mean()*100)
print("std: %",accuracies_lr.std()*100)

scores_lr = cross_val_score(lr, X_balanced, y_balanced, scoring='neg_mean_absolute_error', cv=10,)
print ("MAE (mean absolute error): %" , scores_lr.mean())


# Errors
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error

mae_lr = mean_absolute_error(lr.predict(X_test), y_test)
mse_lr = mean_squared_error(lr.predict(X_test), y_test)
rmse_lr = np.sqrt(mse_lr)
print('Mean Absolute Error (MAE): %.2f' % mae_lr)
print('Mean Squared Error (MSE): %.2f' % mse_lr)
print('Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): %.2f' % rmse_lr)


# Cohen - Matthew Score
from sklearn.metrics import cohen_kappa_score, matthews_corrcoef

print("Cohen Score",cohen_kappa_score(y_test, y_pred))
print("Matthew Score",matthews_corrcoef(y_test, y_pred))

recall_lr = metrics.recall_score(y_test, y_pred)
precision_lr = metrics.precision_score(y_test, y_pred)
accuracy_lr = score

sns.heatmap(cm1, annot=True, fmt=".1f", linewidths=.3, 
        square = True, cmap = 'PuBu')
plt.ylabel('Actual label')
plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
plt.title('Accuracy Score: {0}'.format(score), size = 12)
plt.show()
print("\n")

accuracies_dt = cross_val_score(estimator = dt, X = X_balanced, y = y_balanced, cv = 10)
print("Train Accuracy (mean): %",accuracies_dt.mean()*100)
print("std: %",accuracies_dt.std()*100)

scores_dt = cross_val_score(dt, X_balanced, y_balanced, scoring='neg_mean_absolute_error', cv=10,)
print ("MAE (mean): %" , scores_dt.mean())
print("\n")

mae_dt = mean_absolute_error(dt.predict(X_test), y_test)
mse_dt = mean_squared_error(dt.predict(X_test), y_test)
rmse_dt = np.sqrt(mse_dt)
print('Mean Absolute Error (MAE): %.2f' % mae_dt)
print('Mean Squared Error (MSE): %.2f' % mse_dt)
print('Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): %.2f' % rmse_dt)
print("\n")

print("Cohen Score",cohen_kappa_score(y_test, y_pred))
print("Matthew Score",matthews_corrcoef(y_test, y_pred))

recall_dt = metrics.recall_score(y_test, y_pred)
precision_dt = metrics.precision_score(y_test, y_pred)

from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score, roc_curve
plt.figure()
models_dict = [
    {'label': 'Logistic Regression',
    'model': lr},
    {'label': 'K Nearest Neighbors',
    'model': classifier},
    {'label': 'Random Forest',
    'model': rf},
    {'label': 'Decision Tree',
    'model': dt},
    {'label': 'Gaussian Nave Bayes',
    'model': gaussiannb},
    {'label': 'XGBoost',
    'model': xgb}
]

for m in models_dict:
    auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, m['model'].predict(X_test))
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, m['model'].predict_proba(X_test)[:,1])
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label='%s ROC (area = %0.2f)' % (m['label'], auc))

plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1],'r--')
plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
plt.xlabel('1-Specificity(False Positive Rate)')
plt.ylabel('Sensitivity(True Positive Rate)')
plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic')
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.show()

  • Accuracy: overall performance of the model
  • Precision: how much positive records we predicted correctly
  • Recall: out of actual positive records, how much of them are classified as positive
  • F1 score: mixture of precision and recall

5. Conclusion¶

In my opinion, we need to select our final model based on RECALL score since the goal of the bank marketing is to acquire more clients. We don't want to miss the opportunity to market our potential clients UNLESS the cost of each contact exceeds the potential benefit.¶

  • In summary, the Logistic Model presented the highest recall score among other models.
  • 85% of the clients who suscribed a term deposit were classified correctly.
  • Out of clients who actually subscribed the term deposit, 80% of them are classified correctly.
  • Out of the clients we predicted as positive actually, 43% of them subscribed the term deposit.
